Overview¶

Objective: Build a model to predict whether a person will remain in a hypothetical trade union, the United Data Scientists Union (UDSU).

Assume a country with a major trade union for data scientists. Each member pays some dues amount to it each month and gets various benefits such as representation with employers and continuing education. You will be provided a dataset of 2,000 data scientist IDs by your instructor in Week 2. Each ID represents a data scientist who is a current or former member. Your dataset will contain several features such as:

  • Whether the person is a member of the management
  • Number of months the particular data scientist has been a member of the UDSU
  • Financial dues paid (each month, and in total)
  • Gender of the person
  • Status (still a union member; or no longer a member)

Multivariate Plots¶

In [18]:
# grouped bar charts for bivariate distributions of the target with each categorical variable
for c in categorical:
    plot_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=pd.unique(pd_df[c]))
    for i in pd.unique(pd_df[c]):
        plot_df[i] = pd_df[pd_df[c]==i][target].value_counts()/len(pd_df[pd_df[c]==i])
    plot_df = plot_df.transpose()
    plot_df.plot(kind='bar')
    plt.title(c)
    plt.show()

An individual is more likely to leave the union if they:

  • Are not in management
  • Are a US citizen
  • Are unmarried
  • Live outside MO
  • Have a faster internet connection (fiber > DSL > no connection)
  • FeatureA = No
  • FeatueB = No
  • FeatureC = No
  • FeatureD = Yes or No (not Maryville)
  • FeatueE = Yes or No (not Maryville)
  • Have a higher dues frequency (monthly > annually > every 2 years)
  • Use paperless billing
  • Use a non-automatic payment method (mailed or electronic check)

Factors with no significiant effect:

  • Gender
  • ContinuingEd

An individual is more likely to leave the union if they:

  • Have been in the union for less time
  • Pay higher monthly dues
  • Have paid less dues in total (likely because of less time in union)

To explore that last point, let's create a new feature 'AvgMonthlyDues' defined as TotalDues/MonthsInUnion.

Further Pre-Processing¶

In [22]:
# Redefine feature groups based on EDA findings
idx = ['ID']
categorical = ['Management','USAcitizen','Married','StateOfResidence','Connectivity','FeatureA',\
               'FeatureB','FeatureC','FeatureD','FeatureE','FeatureF','DuesFrequency','PaperlessBilling','PaymentMethod']
    # removed 'gender' and 'ContinuingEd' because they were found to have no significant impact on the target
categorical_idx = [s +'_idx' for s in categorical]
categorical_enc = [s+'_enc' for s in categorical]
numeric = ['MonthsInUnion','MonthlyDues'] 
# Removed TotalDues because it is essentially a transformation of the other two numeric features
predictors = categorical + numeric
target = ['LeftUnion']
In [23]:
# import libraries
from pyspark.ml.feature import VectorAssembler, StringIndexer, OneHotEncoder, StandardScaler
from pyspark.ml import Pipeline 
from pyspark.ml.classification import LogisticRegression
In [24]:
# Create and use pipeline to encode and standardize the data, and create features column
indexer = StringIndexer(inputCols=categorical, outputCols=categorical_idx)
ohe = OneHotEncoder(inputCols=categorical_idx,outputCols=categorical_enc)
predictors_enc = categorical_enc + numeric
assembler = VectorAssembler(inputCols=predictors_enc, outputCol='features') 
scaler = StandardScaler(inputCol='features', outputCol='scaledFeatures', withStd=True, withMean=True)
clean = Pipeline(stages=[indexer,ohe,assembler,scaler])
In [25]:
# Encode, standardize, and assemble predictors
clean_df = clean.fit(df).transform(df)
In [26]:
# Convert target variable LeftUnion to 1 for Yes (left union) and 0 for No (stayed in union)
import pyspark.sql.functions as F
if 'LeftUnion_enc' not in clean_df.columns:
    clean_df = clean_df.withColumn('LeftUnion_enc',F.when(clean_df.LeftUnion=='Yes',1).otherwise(0))

import pyspark.sql.functions as F
import pyspark.sql.types as T
to_array = F.udf(lambda v: v.toArray().tolist(), T.ArrayType(T.FloatType()))
clean_df = clean_df.withColumn('scaledFeatures_array', to_array('scaledFeatures'))
clean_df_pandas = clean_df.toPandas()
import numpy as np
x = clean_df_pandas.scaledFeatures_array
X = np.array([np.array(xi) for xi in x])
Y = np.array(clean_df_pandas.LeftUnion_enc.values)
from sklearn import decomposition
pca = decomposition.PCA(n_components=n)
pca.fit(X)
X = pca.transform(X)

Try different numbers of components

In [55]:
pca_accuracy_dict = {}
for n in range(1,6):
    x = clean_df_pandas.scaledFeatures_array
    X = np.array([np.array(xi) for xi in x])
    Y = np.array(clean_df_pandas.LeftUnion_enc.values)
    
    pca = decomposition.PCA(n_components=n)
    pca.fit(X)
    X = pca.transform(X)
    X_data = list([list(xi) for xi in X])
    pca_data = pd.DataFrame(data={'features':X_data,'label':Y})
    PC=list(['PC'+str(i) for i in range(1,n+1)])
    pca_data[PC] = pd.DataFrame(pca_data["features"].to_list())
    
    # create a pyspark version of the pca data
    spark_pca_data = spark.createDataFrame(pca_data.loc[:,pca_data.columns!='features'])
    assembler = VectorAssembler(inputCols=PC, outputCol='features') 
    spark_pca_data = assembler.transform(spark_pca_data)
    # Split the data into train and test data sets
    pca_train, pca_test = spark_pca_data.randomSplit([0.7,0.3],seed=2003)

    # train model
    rf_model = rf.fit(pca_train)
    rf_results = rf_model.transform(pca_test)
    
    # evaluate model
    pca_rf_accuracy = evaluator.evaluate(rf_results,{evaluator.metricName: 'accuracy'})
    pca_accuracy_dict[n]=pca_rf_accuracy
    print(n,'components -> accuracy =',pca_rf_accuracy)
    
    # scree plot
    PC_values = np.arange(pca.n_components_) + 1
    plt.plot(PC_values, pca.explained_variance_ratio_, 'o-', linewidth=2, color='blue')
    plt.title('Scree Plot: num_components = ' + str(n))
    plt.xlabel('Principal Component')
    plt.ylabel('Variance Explained')
    plt.show()

Conclusions and Reflections¶

The best model I generated was a random forest model using 3 principle components. The accuracy of this model (78.6%) improved on the accuracy of a blind guess (73.3%) by a significant margin (5.3%). The random forest algorithm utilized the information provided to get more accurate predictions, and the principle component analysis mitigated the overfitting problem.

With more time, I would explore other models and the influence of PCA on the other models used, not just the best performing one. However, it was reasonable of me to assume that the best performing model without PCA would still be the best performing model when using PCA.
